# Skill library execution

Battle-tested workflow skills live on disk (instructions + bash tooling). They are NOT Cursor-native, but they are plain markdown + scripts: read the SKILL.md and follow it step-by-step, running its bash from the terminal.

Routing (match task → skill, then read `~/.claude/skills/<name>/SKILL.md`):
- Bug, error, "why is this broken", 500s → `investigate` (Iron Law: no fixes without root-cause investigation first; regression test with every fix)
- Ship, deploy, push, create PR → `ship`
- QA / test the site / find bugs → `qa` · headless browser driving → `browse`
- Code review / check the diff → `review`
- Save progress / resume where I left off → `checkpoint`
- Security audit → `cso` · code health → `health`
- UI aesthetics: pick from `~/.agents/skills/<aesthetic>/` (bento, premium, clean, editorial, …)

Rules of use: follow the skill exactly (don't summarize or skip steps); skill instructions yield to explicit user instructions; if a skill's preamble scripts fail in this environment, continue with its core workflow and note the gap.

# Debugging Iron Law (applies even without loading the skill)

NO FIXES WITHOUT ROOT-CAUSE INVESTIGATION. Read errors, trace the path, check recent diffs, reproduce — then hypothesize, verify the hypothesis with evidence, fix the root cause minimally, and add a regression test that fails pre-fix. Three failed hypotheses → stop and question the architecture.
